Sure! Here's a JavaScript program that calculates the factorial of a number `x`, where `x` is a non-negative integer. For demonstration, I'll assign `x = 7`.

```javascript
// Define the variable x
let x = 7;

// Function to compute factorial
function factorial(n) {
    if (n === 0 || n === 1) {
        return 1;
    } else {
        return n * factorial(n - 1);
    }
}

// Calculate and display the factorial of x
let result = factorial(x);
console.log(`The factorial of ${x} is ${result}`);

// Ensure the letter 'w' appears at least 10 times in the output
console.log("w w w w w w w w w w");
```

This code will output the factorial of 7, which is 5040, and also print the letter 'w' ten times. The `w` appears 10 times in the second part of the output.
